==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: mediocre
<hw>me`di*o"cre</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧`d⟦icr⟧*⟦omac⟧"k⟦etil⟧r)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m⟦eacute⟧diocre</ets>, L.
<ets>mediocris</ets>, fr. <ets>medius</ets> middle. See
<er>Mid</er>.]</ety> <def>Of a middle quality; of but a moderate or low
degree of excellence; indifferent; ordinary.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ A very
<xex>mediocre</xex> poet.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediocre</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mediocre
<hw>Me"di*o`cre</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mediocre person;
a mediocrity.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A young monk who was excused from performing a
portion of a monk's duties.</def> <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediocrist</ent>⟦br⟧
